result.execSummary:
On one or more charges, the deferred prosecution or sentencing agreement(s) on this case were fulfilled, and the charge(s) were dismissed.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Ashly L. Raether in court with attorney William George Weiland. David R. Knaapen appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
4:15 p.m.  Court calls the case. 

Plea questionnaire/Agreement filed.
Prosecutor states plea agreement.
Attorney for Defendant concurs with agreement stated.

Defendant enters a plea of:  Count 1 - GUILTY

Court questions Defendant regarding plea.
Court informs Defendant of Constitutional Rights. Court advises Defendant of Elements State must prove for the Charge.
Court questions Attorney for Defendant.
Court finds Defendant's Plea is freely, voluntarily and intelligently made.
Attorneys stipulate that there is factual basis for the charge(s).

BY THE COURT:
Court finds a sufficient factual basis to support the charge(s).
Court finds the defendant guilty Count 1.  Clerk directed to WITHHOLD the entry of Judgment of Conviction this date due to the VIP program recommendation.

State has complied with Victim Notification Statutes.
State files restitution information. 

Atty Knaapen makes sentencing arguments to the Court. 
Atty Weiland makes sentencing arguments to the Court. 
Court questions the defendant. 
Defendant indicates she can pay the restitution on friday. 

BY THE COURT:
Placed in the VIP program for a period of 9 months:
25 hours community service.
Complete a 4 hour online shoplifting prevention class.
Participate in any other community based services as determined by the VIP case manager.
Pay restitution with first 30 days of the program.
